<title>
Acquired resistance of lung adenocarcinomas to gefitinib or erlotinib is associated with a second mutation in the EGFR kinase domain.
</title>

<text>

<sections.0>
Introduction
omatic gain-of-function mutations in exons encoding the epidermal growth factor receptor () tyrosine kinase domain are found in about 10% of non-small cell lung cancers (s) from the nited tates [1,2,3], with higher percentages observed in east sia [2,4,5,6]. ome 90% of -associated mutations occur as either multi-nucleotide in-frame deletions in exon 19, involving elimination of four amino acids, eu-rg-lu-la, or as a single nucleotide substitution at nucleotide 2573 (β†’) in exon 21, resulting in substitution of arginine for leucine at position 858 (858). oth of these mutations are associated with sensitivity to the small-molecule kinase inhibitors gefitinib or erlotinib [1,2,3]. nfortunately, nearly all patients who experience marked improvement on these drugs eventually develop progression of disease. hile  mutations have been associated with some cases of primary resistance to gefitinib or erlotinib [7], mechanisms underlying β€�acquiredβ€� or β€�secondaryβ€� resistance are unknown.
cquired resistance to kinase-targeted anticancer therapy has been most extensively studied with imatinib, an inhibitor of the aberrant - kinase, in chronic myelogenous leukemia (). utations in the  kinase domain are found in 50%β€“90% of patients with secondary resistance to the drug (reviewed in [8]). uch mutations, which cluster in four distinct regions of the  kinase domain (the  binding loop, 315, 351, and the activation loop), interfere with binding of imatinib to  [9,10,11]. rystallographic studies of various  mutants predict that most should remain sensitive to inhibitors that bind  with less stringent structural requirements. sing this insight, new small-molecule inhibitors have been identified that retain activity against the majority of imatinib-resistant - mutants [12,13].
lthough imatinib inhibits different kinases in various diseases (- in ,  or -alpha in gastrointestinal stromal tumors [s], and -alpha in hypereosinophilic syndrome []) (reviewed in [14]), some tumors that become refractory to treatment with imatinib appear to have analogous secondary mutations in the kinase-coding domain of the genes encoding these three enzymes. or example, in , a commonly found mutation is a β†’ single nucleotide change that replaces threonine with isoleucine at position 315 (315) in the  kinase domain [9,10,11]. n  and , respectively, the analogous 670 mutation in  and 674 mutation in -alpha have been associated with acquired resistance to this drug [15,16].
o determine whether lung cancers that acquire clinical resistance to either gefitinib or erlotinib display additional mutations in the  kinase domain, we have examined the status of  exons 18 to 24 in tumors from five patients who initially responded but subsequently progressed while on these drugs. hese exons were also assessed in tumor cells from a sixth patient whose disease rapidly recurred while on gefitinib therapy after complete gross tumor resection. ecause of the association of  mutations with primary resistance to gefitinib and erlotinib [7], we also examined the status of  in tumor cells from these six patients. n an effort to explain the selective advantage of cells with a newly identified β€�resistanceβ€� mutation in β€”a 790 amino acid substitutionβ€”we further characterized the drug sensitivity of putatively resistant  mutants versus wild-type or drug-sensitive  mutants, using both a  cell line fortuitously found to contain the 790 mutation and lysates from cells transiently transfected with wild-type and mutant  c. DNAs.
