<sections.3>
Discussion
pecific mutations in the tyrosine kinase domain of  are associated with sensitivity to either gefitinib or erlotinib, but mechanisms of acquired resistance have not yet been reported. ased upon analogous studies in other diseases with another kinase inhibitor, imatinib, a single amino acid substitution from threonine to methionine at position 790 in the wild-type  kinase domain was predicted to lead to drug resistance, even before the association of exon 19 and 21 mutations of  with drug responsiveness in  was reported. he 790 mutation was shown in vitro in the context of wild-type  to confer resistance to gefitinib [21] and a related quinazoline inhibitor, 153035 [22].
e show here, through molecular analysis of tumor material from three patients and one  cell line, as well as additional biochemical studies, that acquired clinical drug resistance to gefitinib or erlotinib is indeed associated with the 790 mutation. mportantly, we find that the 790 mutation confers drug resistance not just to wild-type  but also to mutant s associated with clinical responsiveness to  tyrosine kinase inhibitors [1,2,3]. ur results further demonstrate that an analogous mechanism of acquired resistance exists for imatinib and  tyrosine kinase inhibitors (able 3), despite the fact that the various agents target different kinases in distinct diseases.
n tumors from patients not treated with either gefitinib or erlotinib, the 2369 β†’ mutation (790) appears to be extremely rare. e have not identified this mutation in 155 tumors (see above), and among nearly 1,300 lung cancers in which analysis of  exons 18 to 21 has been performed [1,2,3,4,5,6], only one tumor (which also harbored an 858 mutation) was reported to contain the 790 mutation. hether the patient from which this tumor was resected had received gefitinib or erlotinib is unclear, and the report did not note an association with acquired resistance to either drug [5].
ow tumor cells bearing the 790 mutation emerge within gefitinib- or erlotinib-treated patients is a matter of investigation. ubclones bearing this mutation could arise de novo during treatment. owever, based upon analogous studies in , it is also possible that  subclones bearing this secondary mutation pre-exist within the primary tumor clone in individual patients, albeit at low frequency [23]. n either scenario, treatment with gefitinib or erlotinib subsequently allows these resistant subclones to become apparent, because most cells bearing sensitivity-conferring mutations die, while cells with the 790 mutation persist.
rom analysis of the crystal structure of the  kinase domain bound to erlotinib, it is has been shown that the wild-type threonine residue at position 790 is located in the hydrophobic -binding pocket of the catalytic region, where it forms a critical hydrogen bond with the drug [24]. he related compound, gefitinib, is predicted to interact with this threonine residue as well. ubstitution of the threonine at position 790 by a larger residue like methionine would probably result in steric clash with the aromatic moieties on these two drugs [25]. y contrast,  would likely not depend on the accessibility of the same hydrophobic cavity and is therefore probably not affected by the incorporation of a bulky methionine side chain [25]. onsistent with this, the 790 mutation has been shown not to abrogate the catalytic activity of wild-type  [22].
he 790 mutation could also affect the kinase activity or alter the substrate specificity of mutant s, such that a proliferative advantage would be conferred upon cells bearing the mutation. onsistent with this, the 1975  cell line reported here to contain both 790 and 858 did not to our knowledge undergo any prior treatment with gefitinib or erlotinib; the doubly mutated cells must have become dominant over time through multiple passages in vitro. his scenario could explain the seemingly contradictory report by others who found the 1975 cell line to be highly sensitive to gefitinib [18]; our 1975 cells could represent a subclone that emerged over time. nalysis of earlier passages of 1975 cells for the 790 mutation would be informative in this regard.
