n some of the patient specimens analyzed, the actual sequencing peaks demonstrating the 790 mutation were smaller than originally anticipated. hese results differ from those of acquired resistance mutation in  [10],  [15,27], and  [16]. owever, in contrast to all of these diseases, in which tumor cells are readily accessible, lung-cancer-related tumors are more difficult to access, as illustrated by the limited manner in which we were able to obtain tumor cells from various sites of disease (see igure 1). oreover, re-biopsy of patients with lung cancer is not routinely performed. he use of position emission tomography scans to identify the most metabolically active lesions for biopsy could possibly circumvent this factor in the future, as long as such lesions are resectable. dditionally, as more molecularly tailored treatment options become available for lung cancer, re-biopsy of progressive sites of disease should become a standard procedure, especially for patients on clinical trials of targeted agents.
